    <section id="new-diagnosis" class="content-section content-urgent">
      <div class="urgent-box">
        <h2>💙 Just received a diagnosis?</h2>
        <p>Take a breath. CKD is serious, but it is manageable — often for years. Here is what matters most in the first week:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Get your cat eating</strong> — this is the most urgent priority. It does not have to be a kidney diet. It just has to be food.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask for a phosphorus number</strong> specifically — not just "the bloodwork looks okay."</li>
          <li><strong>Ask about IRIS staging</strong> — this gives you a framework for what you are dealing with.</li>
          <li><strong>Do not change everything at once.</strong> Abrupt diet changes in a sick cat often make things worse.</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="{{ '/conditions/ckd-treatment/' | url }}" class="btn btn-primary btn-sm">Treatment options →</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="what-is-ckd" class="content-section">
      <h2>What is CKD?</h2>
      <p>Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) — also called Chronic Renal Failure (CRF) — is a progressive, irreversible reduction in kidney function. The kidneys lose their ability to filter waste, regulate fluids, and produce certain hormones.</p>
      <p>It is extremely common in senior cats. Some estimates suggest over a third of cats over age 12 have some degree of CKD. That does not make the diagnosis easier to hear — but it means there is a substantial body of knowledge about managing it well.</p>
      <p>We managed CKD across five cats: Minou had both CKD and diabetes. Bruce was managed for two to three years before we chose home euthanasia. Yams had CKD alongside stomatitis and hypertension. Milton and Sorbet are both in early-stage management now.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>The core insight:</strong> CKD management is not about returning the kidneys to normal. It is about slowing progression, managing symptoms, and keeping your cat comfortable and eating. Those are different goals — and they change how you think about every decision.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="iris-staging" class="content-section">
      <h2>IRIS Staging — What Stage Is Your Cat?</h2>
      <p>The International Renal Interest Society (IRIS) staging system is the standard framework vets use to categorize CKD severity. It is based primarily on creatinine, with sub-staging for blood pressure and urine protein. Understanding it helps you ask better questions.</p>
      <div class="iris-grid">
        <div class="iris-stage iris-1">
          <div class="iris-num">I</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Minimal</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">&lt; 140 µmol/L</div>
          <p>Early disease. Often no symptoms. Detected by SDMA or urinalysis. Best time to start management — early intervention makes the biggest difference.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="iris-stage iris-2">
          <div class="iris-num">II</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Mild</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">140–250 µmol/L</div>
          <p>Mild symptoms may appear — increased thirst, subtle weight changes. Most cats are diagnosed here. Excellent prognosis with consistent management. Milton and Sorbet are here.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="iris-stage iris-3">
          <div class="iris-num">III</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Moderate</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">251–440 µmol/L</div>
          <p>More noticeable symptoms — nausea, appetite loss, weight loss. Treatment becomes more active. Quality of life focus intensifies. Bruce spent significant time here.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="iris-stage iris-4">
          <div class="iris-num">IV</div>
          <div class="iris-label">Severe</div>
          <div class="iris-creat">&gt; 440 µmol/L</div>
          <p>Significant symptoms. Comfort becomes the primary goal. Supportive care over aggressive intervention.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--amber">
        <strong>Staging is a guide, not a sentence.</strong> Many cats live well beyond what their stage might suggest. Use it to inform treatment decisions — not to predict how much time you have.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="lab-results" class="content-section">
      <h2>Lab Results — What the Numbers Actually Mean</h2>
      <p>Understanding the markers lets you track trends yourself and ask sharper questions at every appointment. Always ask for the actual values — not just "normal" or "a bit elevated."</p>
      <div class="labs-table">
        <div class="lab-row lab-header">
          <span>Marker</span><span>What it measures</span><span>What to watch for</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>Creatinine</strong></span>
          <span>Primary kidney function marker</span>
          <span>Trend over time matters more than a single reading. Dehydration can elevate it temporarily.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>BUN</strong></span>
          <span>Blood urea nitrogen — also affected by diet and hydration</span>
          <span>High BUN + high creatinine = kidney. High BUN + normal creatinine = often dietary or dehydration.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>SDMA</strong></span>
          <span>Earlier detection marker — catches loss before creatinine rises</span>
          <span>If it is not on your panel, ask for it. Especially useful for monitoring Stage 1 and 2.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row lab-highlight">
          <span><strong>Phosphorus</strong></span>
          <span>Mineral the damaged kidney cannot clear</span>
          <span>Elevated phosphorus accelerates kidney damage. Ask for a specific target — see below.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="lab-row">
          <span><strong>Potassium</strong></span>
          <span>Electrolyte — CKD cats often become depleted</span>
          <span>Low potassium causes muscle weakness and worsens kidney function. Supplement if low.</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="phosphorus" class="content-section">
      <h2>Phosphorus — The Number Your Vet May Underemphasise</h2>
      <p>Phosphorus management is the most important dietary intervention in CKD. Damaged kidneys cannot clear phosphorus efficiently, and elevated levels accelerate kidney damage further.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>Ask specifically:</strong> "What is the phosphorus level, and what is our target range?" IRIS guidelines: below 1.45 mmol/L for Stage 2, below 1.61 mmol/L for Stage 3. If you do not get a specific number, push for one.
      </div>
      <p>Control phosphorus through diet first, then binders if needed. More on binders in the <a href="{{ '/conditions/ckd-treatment/' | url }}">treatment section</a>.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="diet" class="content-section">
      <h2>Diet and Food</h2>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Food in the cat first.</strong> A cat who refuses the kidney diet but eats their regular food should eat their regular food. Starvation causes liver damage far faster than slightly elevated phosphorus. Do not let perfect be the enemy of eating.
      </div>
      <h3>Wet food matters</h3>
      <p>Hydration is critical — damaged kidneys cannot concentrate urine effectively, leading to chronic dehydration. Wet food significantly increases water intake and is one of the most impactful changes you can make.</p>
      <h3>On prescription kidney diets</h3>
      <p>Kidney diets restrict phosphorus and protein. The evidence for phosphorus restriction is solid. But they only help if your cat eats them. Introduce gradually, mixed with familiar food. For cats who will not transition, manage phosphorus through binders and careful label reading instead.</p>
      <div class="content-callout">
        <strong>US and Canada note:</strong> Common prescription kidney diets include Royal Canin Renal, Hill's k/d, and Purina NF. Phosphorus content varies significantly between formulations — ask for the specific phosphorus percentage, not just the brand name.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="vet-conversations" class="content-section">
      <h2>Vet Conversations</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li>What is my cat's IRIS stage, and what does that mean for treatment right now?</li>
        <li>What is the phosphorus level specifically, and what is our target range?</li>
        <li>Is SDMA on the panel? If not, can we add it?</li>
        <li>Has uraemic nausea been considered as a cause of appetite loss?</li>
        <li>Are we monitoring blood pressure? When was it last measured?</li>
        <li>Is my cat a candidate for home sub-Q fluids?</li>
        <li>Are we optimising for longevity, quality of life, or both — and are we aligned on that?</li>
        <li>What would you change if this were your cat?</li>
      </ul>
